TYPES OF SCHEMA--
1. STAR SCHEMA [most common] - 1 fact table in the center and many dimension tables surrounding it..
            Used in data warehouses / reporting
            Structure:
            Dimension Tables
            (customer, product)
                │
                ▼
            Fact Table
            (sales, orders)

            Example:
            Fact Table → sales (amount, quantity, date_id, product_id)
            Dimension → customer (name, city)
            Dimension → product (name, category)
    ✅ Why it's used in production
    Simple design
    Fast queries
    Easy for BI tools

2. SNOWFLAKE SCHEMA - Extension of Star Schema (more normalized)
        Structure:
        Fact → Dimension → Sub-dimension
        Example:
        Product → Category → Department

        ✅ Pros
        Less data redundancy
        More organized
        ❌ Cons
        More joins → slower queries
        🔹 Use case:
        When data is complex & large

3. Medallion Architecture - Bronze → Silver → Gold

4. Normalized Schema (OLTP Systems)- Used in transactional databases
        Features:
        Data split into multiple tables
        Avoids duplication
        Example:
        Customer Table
        Order Table
        Product Table

5. GALAXY/ FACT constallation schema - multiple fact table with shared[one] dimension table
